FRAMEWORKS - Cambridge make large savings through Jisc Frameworks (e.g. OCRE). The IT Director wants to see Jisc provide more frameworks (IDP, VLE) as the savings made are very important to justifying annual Jisc membership subscription

ENVIRONMENT: The University is very interested in any 'Green' initiatives and 'Smart Cities', encouraging departments and colleges across the University in reducing their environmental impacts. This is due to such a large carbon footprint. The University is committed to continual environmental improvement, including through a 'science based target' to reduce its energy-related carbon emissions to absolute zero by 2048, with a steep 75% decrease on 2015 emissions by 2030.

Access and Identity management: There is a lot of A&I services across Cambridge, they are robust but are increasingly slowing down other activities due to their complexity *Identity management - currently have two single sign on systems which can be problematic *CISO is carrying out a full review of their identity and access management infrastructure, and when complete they would like to explore IDP management solutions

Digital Capabilities: There is a increasing recognition that the university need to better support the digital skills of staff with LinkedIn learning providing key content supported by Jisc BDC. As part of OurCambridge>Digital Workplace this is key priority for the inistution

Cloud: There is growing demand from a number of parts of the university to mke use of Cloud technologies. UIS want to look at how they can better support these needs. Including: *Academics want to make use of MS Azure, and anticipate spending several thousands of pounds per year *Cambridge University Press are to be looking to shut down Data Centres and as a result significantly increase their use of AWS and are interested in the benefits of AWS Direct connect to save costs *Judge Business School are looking to build more apps and make use of tools in MS Azure

As part of this review is to look at the Jisc enhanced DDOS options and potentially extend their current CSP use to protect entire University. Digital Preservation: https://www.cam.ac.uk/stories/digital_preservation_programme Library has been working very hard to get a co-ordinated digital preservation approach across the university. Digital preservation is fundamental to Cambridge University Libraries? (CUL) stewardship of digital content. Digital preservation is currently considered one of CUL?s highest risks. CUL is committed to working collaboratively, holistically and cross-departmentally in order to address digital preservation concerns over the coming six years In order for CUL to be recognised as a twenty-first century research library, to support world-class digital collections, and facilitate the education, learning and research needs of the University of Cambridge (the University), transitioning to Business-As-Usual (BAU) digital preservation functions are fundamental. For the past twenty years, CUL has taken a project-by-project approach to digital preservation, however this is no longer suitable
